    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-09-25T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-09-25T02:00:00-05:00" n="360"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d360">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.113 Senate Investigation/69: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-09-25T15:00:00+08:00"
                            >September 25, 1934—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received September 25—11:25 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>429. The following telegram has been received from Gauss<note n="38"
                        xml:id="d360fn38">Clarence E. Gauss, Counselor of Legation in China.</note>
                    at Nanking.</p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>“September 24, noon. The Political Vice Minister for Foreign Affairs<note
                            n="39" xml:id="d360fn39">Hsu Mo.</note> sent for me this morning to say
                        that General Chiang Kai Shek has urged the Foreign Office to press its
                        request already made through the Chinese Minister at Washington<note n="40"
                            xml:id="d360fn40">See memorandum by the Secretary of State, September
                            18, <ref target="#pg_438">p. 438</ref>.</note> for disclosure to Chinese
                        Government of names of Chinese officials and Military officers who received
                        commissions in arms transactions.”</p>
                </quote>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
